# Cursor Rules - Aashish Prakash's Projects

## General Coding Standards

### Python
- Use type hints for function signatures
- Follow PEP 8 style guide
- Use descriptive variable and function names
- Add docstrings to all functions and classes
- Prefer list comprehensions over map/filter when readable
- Use `pathlib` for file path operations
- Handle exceptions explicitly; avoid bare `except` clauses

### Code Organization
- Keep functions focused and single-purpose
- Limit function length to ~50 lines when possible
- Group related functionality into classes or modules
- Use meaningful file and directory names

### Documentation
- Comment complex logic and business rules
- Keep comments up-to-date with code changes
- Use inline comments sparingly; prefer self-documenting code
- Maintain README files in project directories

### Testing
- Write unit tests for critical business logic
- Use descriptive test names that explain the scenario
- Follow Arrange-Act-Assert pattern in tests
- Mock external dependencies in unit tests

## Project-Specific Rules

### D2k/ext-data-subscription
- **Documentation Location**: `/Users/aashishprakash/Projects/D2k/documentation/ews-data-subscription/`
- All documentation for ext-data-subscription must be created in the documentation folder, not in the project base folder

### Dagster Projects
- Use `uv` as package manager (never `pip` or `poetry`)
- Each course is an independent Python project
- Always `cd` into the course directory first
- Run commands with `uv run` prefix: `uv run dg dev`, `uv run pytest`
- The `completed/` directory is read-only reference material

### Data Engineering
- Use descriptive names for ETL pipelines and data assets
- Document data sources, transformations, and destinations
- Include data quality checks in pipelines
- Log important processing steps and errors
- Handle missing or invalid data gracefully

## Version Control
- Write clear, descriptive commit messages
- Use conventional commits format when possible
- Keep commits focused on single changes
- Don't commit sensitive data (credentials, API keys)

## Dependencies
- Pin dependency versions in production
- Document why specific versions are required
- Keep dependencies updated regularly
- Use virtual environments for all Python projects

## Error Handling
- Log errors with sufficient context for debugging
- Use appropriate error types
- Provide helpful error messages
- Clean up resources in finally blocks or context managers

## Performance
- Profile before optimizing
- Document performance-critical sections
- Use appropriate data structures
- Consider memory usage for large datasets
